SIMPLE: patio
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Patio
<hw>Pa"ti*o</hw> <pr>(p⟦aum⟧"t⟦esl⟧*⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Sp., a court]</ety> <fld>(Metal)</fld> <def>A paved yard or floor
where ores are cleaned and sorted, or where ore, salt, mercury, etc.,
are trampled by horses, to effect intermixture and
amalgamation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The <xex>patio process</xex> is used to reduce silver
ores by amalgamation.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In Spain, Spanish America, etc., a court or
courtyard of a house or other building; esp., an inner court open to the
sky.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pr>(p⟦acr⟧t"⟦esl⟧*⟦omac⟧`)</pr> <def>A usually paved
area adjacent to a dwelling, used for outdoor lounging, dining,
receptions of guests, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>patio furniture</ent>⟦br⟧
